@pcadabam made requested changes:
- Created a class `RecoveryHelper` containing all the logic for persisting and recovery.
- Created a class `Guid` containing methods for creating and handling guids.

@kadaan this approach looks good for the time being (pending the 1 question I had). A few final thoughts before I merge this:
- I still think that instead of passing in a `CommitAction` to `ParallelRunner.renamePath`, the method should just return a `List<(Future, Method Params)>`, but your approach works to so we can stick to this for now; I think the `ParallelRunner` doesn't have the right level of abstraction so that is part of the reason too
- Down the line, the `BaseDataPublisher` needs to be re-designed - the class has become too obtuse and should be broken down into simple components - but that is a question for another day

@sahilTakiar One concern I have is that the original BaseDataPublisher did a _ton_ of stuff and there aren't really many tests around it.  For instance, there are different behaviors when publishData(state) is called vs. publishData(state[]).  I've tried to keep this behavior the same as before while also removing a bunch of different code branching and duplication.  

I'm slightly concerned that I may have inadvertently changed some behavior.  My biggest concern is that Task.publishTaskData behavior has changed, but as I don't really know that code path it is hard for me to say what the change could be.  I noticed one change in behavior and am updating the PR to account for that.  

It also seems like the proposed way of determining if a WorkUnit can be marked as COMMITTED won't work when `Task.shouldPublishDataInTask()` returns `true`.  @sahilTakiar, can you look at this and see what you think?

@kadaan yes I have the same concern about the lack of unit tests for this. If I have some time in the near future I may work on fixing that.

For the `Task.shouldPublishDataInTask()` method what was the specific concern you had? There isn't anything that jumps out to me that could cause problems. Also, as long as the publisher doesn't throw an error for the job it will be marked as committed (line 241 of `Task.java`).

Let me know if you all change have been committed, then I will do the merge.

@sahilTakiar: I'm wondering how this will work correctly with S3 given that job based publishing move/renames a folder at a time and that is not an atomic action.  #572 handles this differently by switching to renaming/moving the individual files within the folder. 

#569 allows for exactly-once publishing, but it too won't work correctly with S3.  For instance, while running a FsRenameCommitStep it could fail to copy the entire folder.  The root of the folder will exist and when it is retried it will be skipped because `this.dstFs.exists(this.dstPath)` return `true`.

As I said in my last comment on #572, I still want to get this in. It is a high priority for us (as well as you), but making sure this works with a wide range of possible filesystems is also important. We made good progress today on getting gobblin running in our stage environment and so I should be able to get back to #572 soon.  Please let me know how you want to proceed.
